cover some of the digital marketing articles that have been shared around the 3 Door Digital office over the last couple of weeks. We share the posts we discuss in our weekly hangout as we chat about them. Be sure to follow #3dddrm to stay up to date and join in the conversation. The hangout takes place every Wednesday at 10am GMT.</p><p> <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/creative-content/orange-line-break/" rel="attachment wp-att-1687"><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-1687" title="orange-line-break" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://www.heavy.com/news/2012/11/israel-hamas-twitter-war-could-get-idf-account-suspended/">Israel-Hamas Twitter War Could Get IDF Account Suspended | HEAVY</a></strong><br\n/> <strong></strong><a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/HeavySan">Author. Eitan Levine</a></p><p>Since the tension between Israel and Hamas has been increasingly tense over the past week or so, I thought I would start off with an interesting post that may give some insight as to whether high profile twitter accounts have to adhere to the same TOS as the rest of us. To give an example, it seems at first glance that both @IDFSpokesperson and @AlqassamBrigade have clearly violated Twitters TOS’s but have not been banned. Could it be that military, celebrities and other high profile Twitter accounts do not have to adhere to the same TOS’s as everyone else?</p><p> <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/creative-content/orange-line-break/" rel="attachment wp-att-1687"><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-1687" title="orange-line-break" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://techcrunch.com/2012/11/20/trulioo-profile-plus/">With Google’s Former Identity Director As CTO And $2M In New Funding, Trulioo Launches Fake Facebook Profile Detector</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/AnthonyHa">Author. Anthony Ha</a></p><p>Social media just got a little bit harder. Trulioo is a service that analyzes if your Facebook profile is real or not. It can supply you with a multitude of information, including user age, location and phone numbers.</p><p>In the future, Trulioo plans to expand services to provide even more information. Right now you can request a beta account via their website and wait to be approved. Once that happens you can start testing which profiles and which are fake!</p><p> <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/creative-content/orange-line-break/" rel="attachment wp-att-1687"><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-1687" title="orange-line-break" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://unbounce.com/landing-pages/writing-high-converting-copy/">The Flexible Framework for Writing High-Converting Landing Page Copy</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/ContentVerve">Author. Michael Agaard</a></p><p>Landing pages should consist of header, sub-heading, primary information which is &#8220;need to know&#8221; and secondary information which is &#8220;nice to know&#8221;. The most important thing to remember is that &#8220;one size does not fit all&#8221; and you have to be flexible when it comes to writing landing pages. Be clear, concise and to the point. Don&#8217;t leave anything up to the imagination and don&#8217;t be over creative. Some other points to consider are:</p><ul><li>Ensure that you provide concrete data that supports your offer and the title of the page.</li><li>Emphasize aspects and facts that mitigate anxiety and/or compel the prospect to read more.</li><li>Identify a problem and briefly explain how your service or product will solve it.</li></ul><p> <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/creative-content/orange-line-break/" rel="attachment wp-att-1687"><img\ntitle="orange-line-break" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://unbounce.com/conversion-rate-optimization/images-and-conversion-rates/">3 Ways to Increase Your Conversion Rate With Images [Case Studies]</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/GregoryCiotti">Author. Gregory Ciotti</a></p><ol><li>Photos of People Can Increase Empathy</li><li>Make use of Women, Babies and Attractive People where possible</li><li>Photos of Objects Can Increase Trust even if the object is not so related</li></ol><p>Take the extra time to make good product mock-up photos (especially when dealing with digital goods) to help the trust factor on your site.</p><p>Once again this does not apply in every single situation but are &#8220;general good practice&#8221; guidelines.</p><p> <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/creative-content/orange-line-break/" rel="attachment wp-att-1687"><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-1687" title="orange-line-break" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://wpmu.org/reverse-engineer-any-wordpress-website-discover-the-hidden-secrets/">Reverse Engineer Any WordPress Website – Discover The Hidden Secrets</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/wpmuorg">Author. James Dunn</a></p><p>The article discusses the ways in which you can view not only the theme that a WordPress site uses, but also the version number and what plugins are installed. This is a good exercise on your own sites to identify possible security holes (such as broadcasting what version of WordPress you are using) as well as identifying plugins that other sites are using, allowing you to use them on your site.</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/creative-content/orange-line-break/" rel="attachment wp-att-1687"><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-1687" title="orange-line-break" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://www.portent.com/blog/analytics/google-analytics-website-optimization-tips.htm">3 Hidden Optimization Tips in Google Analytics</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/merlayna">Author Aviva Jorstad</a></p><ol><li>Increase conversions from organic search</li></ol><p>Without going into too much detail on the how, there are three questions you can ask yourself after filtering the data from organic search visits (Traffic Sources &gt; Sources &gt; Search &gt; Organic):</p><ul><li>Increase conversions from organic search</li><li>Does the landing page provide relevant information</li><li>Does the landing page have a clear CTA</li></ul><p>To get full instructions on the how, you can visit the <a\nhref="http://www.portent.com/blog/analytics/google-analytics-website-optimization-tips.htm">original post</a>.</p><ol><li>Get the Links you deserve</li></ol><p>By looking into the referral report under traffic sources in Google Analytics you can see which sites are referring traffic to yours. Set the date range to cover the past 6 months and check out the top 50. Think about what is missing and go seek them out. Do some competitor analysis on other niche’s that they have posts on and go get them too!</p><ol><li>Get content and architecture ideas from site search</li></ol><p>If you don’t have site search set up see this post to <a\nhref="http://www.portent.com/blog/analytics/install_google_analytics_site.htm">get it done</a>. Once you have site search and a reasonable amount of data look for searches that have a high “Time after Search” since this indicates a high interest level and a low “% Search Exits”. If this content is not easily accessible to the user then you might want to think about putting it in the top navigation or creating a CTA for it on the homepage.</p><p>I hope you enjoyed our roundup and don’t forget to follow #3dddrm every Wednesday at 10am GMT to join the conversation. Feel free to leave a comment or ask any questions below.</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/wordpress-cro-google-analytics-content-ideas/">Digital Roundup: WordPress, CRO, Google Analytics and Content Ideas</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/gideon-wellins/">Gideon Wellins</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"http://3doordigital.com/wordpress-cro-google-analytics-content-ideas/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:10:"          ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"Notes from 3 Speakers at #ContentMarketingShow";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:123:"http://3doordigital.com/content-marketing-show-2012/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=content-marketing-show-2012";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"http://3doordigital.com/content-marketing-show-2012/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 21 Nov 2012 15:39:34 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Conferences";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"Content Marketing";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2579";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:658:"<p>Yesterday I attended the first Content Marketing Show brought to us by Kelvin Newman who also hosts the extremely popular and ever growing BrightonSEO. Instead of giving brief notes on each presentation I decided to give more detailed notes on the three that stood out the most to me. The presentation I especially enjoyed was [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/content-marketing-show-2012/">Notes from 3 Speakers at #ContentMarketingShow</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/anna-moss/">Anna Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Anna Moss";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5980:"<p><img\nclass="alignleft size-full wp-image-2589" title="content-marketing-show-logo" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/content-marketing-show-logo.gif" alt="Content Marketing Show 2012" width="117" height="117" />Yesterday I attended the first Content Marketing Show brought to us by Kelvin Newman who also hosts the extremely popular and ever growing BrightonSEO.</p><p><img\nclass="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2588" title="c-m-s-text" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/c-m-s-text.gif" alt="" width="574" height="80" style="clear:both;"/></p><p>Instead of giving brief notes on each presentation I decided to give more detailed notes on the three that stood out the most to me. The presentation I especially enjoyed was from Jochen Mebus from Textbroker. When you are receiving numerous content requests every day, you need a clear and concise brief before you can start the work. It becomes very time consuming to email or phone the person requesting the content and asking them for more details. I will definitely be using all the tips given whenever I request content from someone else!</p><p><img\ntitle="orange-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></p><h2>1) Mila MacLean Homburg – Content Marketing Consultant, Site Visibility</h2><p><strong>Tales from a Content Marketing Rookie </strong></p><ul><li>Traditional marketing does matter to your online marketing strategy</li><li>Offline marketing includes who you are speaking to and where your brand exists in the market</li><li>Know your client, what they are expecting and what they want you to produce for them</li><li>Know your audience and who you are targeting, is this different from who and what your client wants to target?</li><li>Good content does not come cheap, make sure you choose the right people</li><li>Use team members within your company who you can trust, different people will have different ideas so speak to a variety of people from developers to your social team</li><li>Keep researching. Make sure you are always up to date on what is coming next, you don’t want to be the last person to do something</li><li>Make sure you are happy to have your name associated with the content that is going out, always do your best work&#8230;it will be around on the web for a long, long time!</li></ul><p><img\ntitle="orange-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></p><h2>2) Stephen Pavlovich – Cofounder, Wish.co.uk</h2><p><strong>Using content to get Press Coverage</strong></p><ul><li>There are four key factors that make for successful PR; the story has to be topical and as responsive as possible, sexual, controversial and celebrity. If you can combine all four aspects then this is ideal.<strong></strong></li><li>None of this has to be expensive, you can take an existing product and change it up to gain attention <strong></strong></li><li>Wish.co.uk had a weekend break for two offer already on the site, turned this into a break for three for Valentine’s Day making it sexual and topical. The story was picked up by the Metro newspaper and sparked a debate on BBC Five.<strong></strong></li><li>Don’t be too scared or too worried to do something and think it will never work<strong></strong></li><li>What would you do if you weren’t afraid? Go from there and actually implement and do some of the things you would otherwise be scared to do</li></ul><p><img\ntitle="orange-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/orange-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></p><h2>3) Jochen Mebus – Vice President Sales Europe, Textbroker</h2><p><strong>Successful Briefs – the key to getting good content</strong></p><ul><li>What you need to do to improve your briefs and how to ensure you get the content you want</li><li>Getting content isn’t a simple process, firstly you have to decide whether you are going to do it yourself, give it to someone else in the business or outsource it</li><li>Whether you give it to someone else in the company or outsource it, if you do not give clear, concise and detailed instructions you might not get what you wanted</li><li>Write a brief with yourself in mind, if you were the author what would you want to know</li><li>The most important things to include in your brief are:<ul><li>What is the overall goal of the content?</li><li>Who is your target audience?</li><li>Describe the preferred style of writing</li><li>What kind of text are you looking for? Supply links to sample sites so you are giving clear examples</li><li>Don’t forget to mention the things you don’t want</li><li>List specific questions the content is meant to answer</li><li>Specify your desired structure for the piece</li><li>Specify any SEO requirements you might have</li><li>Always ask the author to contact you in case they have any other questions. If you don’t make yourself available to them, you could receive something you don’t want</li></ul></li><li>In short if you write a concise briefing that isn’t too short or too long, you are friendly to the author and make yourself available to answer any questions you will get the content you want</li></ul><p>The quality of the speakers and their presentations at the Content Marketing Show were excellent; the above are just the ones that stuck in my mind the most. The day was a huge success and I, along with many others, are looking forward to its return in Spring 2013, so if you missed out on this one be prepared to get your ticket quickly in the springtime.</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/content-marketing-show-2012/">Notes from 3 Speakers at #ContentMarketingShow</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/anna-moss/">Anna Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"http://3doordigital.com/content-marketing-show-2012/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"         ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:77:"Digital Roundup: Social Signals, CRO, Google Analytics and Syndicated Content";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:169:"http://3doordigital.com/social-signals-google-analytics-syndicated-content/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=social-signals-google-analytics-syndicated-content";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:84:"http://3doordigital.com/social-signals-google-analytics-syndicated-content/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 07 Nov 2012 15:00:49 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Digital Roundup";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2540";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:698:"<p>Welcome to another edition of the Digital Roundup. This roundup will cover some of the digital marketing articles that have been shared around the 3 Door Digital office over the last few weeks. We share the posts we discuss in our weekly hangout as we chat about them. Be sure to follow #3dddrm to stay [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/social-signals-google-analytics-syndicated-content/">Digital Roundup: Social Signals, CRO, Google Analytics and Syndicated Content</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/gideon-wellins/">Gideon Wellins</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Gideon Wellins";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5435:"<p>Welcome to another edition of the Digital Roundup. This roundup will cover some of the digital marketing articles that have been shared around the 3 Door Digital office over the last few weeks. We share the posts we discuss in our weekly hangout as we chat about them. Be sure to follow #3dddrm to stay up to date and join in the conversation. The hangout takes place every Wednesday at 10am GMT.</p><p>This week we were discussing a number of different and interesting topics.</p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/g9qmj">Your Guide to Social Signals for SEO</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/jaysondemers">Author. Jason DeMers</a></p><p>Although social signals are always a mystery in terms of rankings it is clear that the importance of social signals are increasing with time. Usually people who come to your site through social networks have a lower bounce rate since they actually wanted to come to your site. I do believe that direct and indirect impacts of social signals will eventually surpass links as the most valuable ranking factor.</p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/li8rl">How I Hijacked Rand Fishkin’s Blog</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/dejanseo">Author. Dan Petrovic</a></p><p>When a duplicate page is created and merged into a main “canonical” document version it will display it’s PageRank, cache, links, info but in Rand’s case also +1′s. Yes, even +1′s. For example if you +1 a designated duplicate, the selected main version will receive the +1′s. Similarly if you +1 the selected main URL the change in +1′s will immediately reflect on any recognised copies. When a copy receives higher PageRank however, and the switch takes place, all links and social signals will be re-assigned to the “winning” version. I am not entirely convinced that authorship will do much to prevent search result swap from a more juiced URL, however it could be a contributing factor or a signal and it doesn’t hurt to have it implemented regardless.</p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/hvu-m">Announcing Enhanced Link Attribution for In-Page Analytics</a></strong></p><p><strong></strong>This update gives us the ability to have multiple links to one page and be able to track which link is preforming better. Until now, when looking at in-page analytics if there is multiple links to one page then it would show the same percentage of clicks over all the links. To enable enhanced link attribution you can follow the instructions below:</p><p>You need to be using the async. version of the analytics tracking code. Then add the following (in red) before _trackPageview;</p><pre>var _gaq = _gaq || [];\n <span style="color: #ff0000;">var pluginUrl =</span>\n<span style="color: #ff0000;"> ''//www.google-analytics.com/plugins/ga/inpage_linkid.js'';</span>\n<span style="color: #ff0000;"> _gaq.push([''_require'', ''inpage_linkid'', pluginUrl]);</span>\n _gaq.push([''_setAccount'', ''UA-XXXXXX-Y'']);\n _gaq.push([''_trackPageview'']);</pre><p>Then simply enable it in the reports</p><ol><li>Click <strong>Admin</strong> at the top of any Analytics page.</li><li>Navigate to the property for which you want to use enhanced link attribution, and click the <strong>Property Settings</strong> tab.</li><li>In the <em>In-Page Analytics</em> section, select the <strong>Use enhanced link attribution</strong> option.</li><li>Click <strong>Apply</strong>.</li></ol><p>Read more about enabling enhanced link attribution <a\nhref="http://support.google.com/analytics/bin/answer.py?hl=en&amp;answer=2558867">here</a></p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/uypkj">What to track in case of lost traffic; a forensic blueprint</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/thegypsy">Author. David Harry</a></p><p>The post describes all the preparatory steps that you should take before starting an SEO campaign. As well as obvious steps such as monitoring Google Analytics &amp; Google Webmaster Tools, it also talks about less obvious steps, such as tracking competitors links and rankings. This could all be valuable data should rankings ever drop.</p><p><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/myude">Why your CRO tests fail</a></strong><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://www.twitter.com/willcritchlow">Author. Will Critchlow</a></p><p>Ensure that the blend of traffic that you are getting is fair. Some important points include:</p><ul><li>Correctly assessing the amount of time needed to run the rest</li><li>Do not peek at the test before it is finished</li><li>Calling the test successful only if it achieves at least 95% confidence.</li></ul><p>To obtain higher level of certainty you must run the test for longer or create another copy of each page in order to spread the traffic more evenly. By following these guidelines you will be more likely to achieve higher certainty in your CRO testing.</p><p>I hope you enjoyed our roundup and don&#8217;t forget to follow #3dddrm every Wednesday at 10am GMT to join the conversation. Feel free to leave a comment or ask any questions below.</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/social-signals-google-analytics-syndicated-content/">Digital Roundup: Social Signals, CRO, Google Analytics and Syndicated Content</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/gideon-wellins/">Gideon Wellins</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"http://3doordigital.com/social-signals-google-analytics-syndicated-content/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"         ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"3 Door Digital is recruiting: 2 roles available!";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:125:"http://3doordigital.com/seo-jobs-manchester-tel-aviv/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=seo-jobs-manchester-tel-aviv";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"http://3doordigital.com/seo-jobs-manchester-tel-aviv/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 31 Oct 2012 07:00:08 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Recruitment";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2069";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:677:"<p>3 Door Digital is on an exciting mission, starting now! We are a small but well established International Digital Marketing Agency with offices in the UK and Israel. Our technical expertise, creative flair and exceptional customer service means clients can rest assured that their online investment is in good hands. 3 Door Digital works with [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/seo-jobs-manchester-tel-aviv/">3 Door Digital is recruiting: 2 roles available!</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/alex-moss/">Alex Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Alex Moss";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12335:"<p>3 Door Digital is on an exciting mission, starting now! We are a small but well established International Digital Marketing Agency with offices in the UK and Israel. Our technical expertise, creative flair and exceptional customer service means clients can rest assured that their online investment is in good hands.</p><p>3 Door Digital works with both national and global brands, many of which have moved away from large marketing firms in order to benefit from our hands on and results driven approach.</p><p>Both positions are full time and office based. To find out more about either position, simply click the job role and more information will appear.</p><div\nid="accordion2" class="accordion"><div\nclass="accordion-group"><div\nclass="accordion-heading"><a\nclass="accordion-toggle" href="#collapseOne" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2"><br\n/> Digital Marketing Manager<br\n/> </a></div><div\nid="collapseOne" class="accordion-body collapse in"><div\nclass="accordion-inner"><p>We will consider candidates in both Countries and select the best candidate regardless of location. This position is Full-Time office based.</p><p>3 Door Digital is looking for a Digital Marketing Manager. This person will handle different aspects of all clients small and large. You need to be enthusiastic about what you do and have the attitude to get things done. Creativity and knowledge of coding is something we would also like to see but is not essential. We are looking for someone with a passion and enthusiasm towards learning about the industry and how Search can really help improve our clients’ business.<strong><strong></strong></strong></p><p>When joining us you commit to:</p><ul><li>Working hard</li><li>Communicating effectively</li><li>Contributing in a creative way</li><li>Thinking outside the box</li><li>Continuing to learn and develop &#8211; off your own back</li><li>Joining us at the pub and on company night outs</li></ul><p><strong><strong><br\n/> In return we will commit to:<br\n/> </strong></strong></p><ul><li>An on-going training program and the backing of all our consultants.</li><li>The potential to work with big brands</li><li>A relaxed and fun working environment</li><li>2 computer screens</li><li>A company lunch once every 2 weeks</li><li>Your birthday off</li><li>+ many other office treats <img\nsrc=''http://3doordigital.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif'' alt='':)'' class=''wp-smiley'' /></li></ul><p><strong\nid="internal-source-marker_0.48900013556703925"><br\n/> Skills / Experience:</strong></p><p>We are looking to find an individual who has excellent English communication skills (both written and oral) and a good eye for detail. You will have an understanding of how the Internet works, specifically the behaviour of search engines, and will be able to display a keen interest in Search and the industry when interviewed. Although not essential, we would like you to have knowledge of on-site including HTML, CSS, PHP and specifically a love for WordPress.</p><p>We would expect you to be the type of individual that actively reads and keeps up to date on Search latest news and developments. Other qualities we look for are passion for what you do and be open to learning new things within Search.</p></div></div></div><div\nclass="accordion-group"><div\nclass="accordion-heading"><a\nclass="accordion-toggle" href="#collapseTwo" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion2"><br\n/> Digital Outreach Coordinator<br\n/> </a></div><div\nid="collapseTwo" class="accordion-body collapse"><div\nclass="accordion-inner"><p>We will consider candidates in both Countries and select the best candidate regardless of location. This position is Full-Time office based.</p><p>If you’re looking for a new, exciting position and your answer is ‘yes’ to the following questions, we want to hear from you:</p><ul><li>Are you enthusiastic?</li><li>Are you competitive?</li><li>Are you creative?</li><li>Do you want to succeed?</li></ul><p><strong><strong><br\n/> When joining us you commit to:<br\n/> </strong></strong></p><ul><li>Working hard</li><li>Communicating effectively</li><li>Contributing in a creative way</li><li>Thinking outside the box</li><li>Continuing to learn and develop &#8211; off your own back</li><li>Joining us at the pub and on company night outs</li></ul><p><strong><strong><br\n/> In return we will commit to:<br\n/> </strong></strong></p><ul><li>An on-going training program and the backing of all our consultants.</li><li>The potential to work with big brands</li><li>A relaxed and fun working environment</li><li>2 computer screens</li><li>A company lunch once every 2 weeks</li><li>Your birthday off</li><li>+ many other office treats!</li></ul><p><strong\nid="internal-source-marker_0.48900013556703925"><br\n/> Job Description:</strong></p><p>We are currently hiring a Digital Outreach Coordinator to join our growing team. The job involves a high level of internet searching as well as building relationships with webmasters, news sites and other online organisations. The successful candidate will be trained in the various aspects of SEO and link building and will become part of a small online marketing team. For those interested in working in SEO, 3 Door Digital  offers a great opportunity.<strong\nid="internal-source-marker_0.48900013556703925"></strong></p><p>Skills / Experience:</p><p><strong\nid="internal-source-marker_0.48900013556703925"></strong>A high level of English, both written and spoken<br\n/> A good sales/marketing personality + Experience<br\n/> Internet Proficiency in Email, Web-Browsing, Spreadsheets<br\n/> The ability to learn quickly and pick up new Internet skills, software, and web-tools.<br\n/> <strong\nid="internal-source-marker_0.48900013556703925"><br\n/> Salary</strong></p><p>Dependent on Experience</p></div></div></div></div><p>To apply for either role, simply fill out the form below. Good luck!</p><div\nclass=''gf_browser_unknown gform_wrapper'' id=''gform_wrapper_4'' ><a\nid=''gf_4'' name=''gf_4'' class=''gform_anchor'' ></a><form\nmethod=''post'' enctype=''multipart/form-data'' target=''gform_ajax_frame_4'' id=''gform_4''  action=''/feed/#gf_4''><div\nclass=''gform_body''><ul\nid=''gform_fields_4'' class=''gform_fields left_label description_below''><li\nid=''field_4_1'' class=''gfield               gfield_contains_required'' ><label\nclass=''gfield_label'' for=''input_4_1_3''>Name<span\nclass=''gfield_required''>*</span></label><div\nclass=''ginput_complex ginput_container'' id=''input_4_1''><span\nid=''input_4_1_3_container'' class=''ginput_left''><input\ntype=''text'' name=''input_1.3'' id=''input_4_1_3'' value='''' tabindex=''1'' /><label\nfor=''input_4_1_3''>First</label></span><span\nid=''input_4_1_6_container'' class='