 we have noticed that WordPress.org users can now review both WordPress plugins and themes. This addition to WordPress Extend now provides more detail into users&#8217; thoughts, rather than the simple voting system that has been provided up until now. Rich Snippet Integration? Rhys kindly reviewed my Facebook Comments plugin. From looking at Google&#8217;s Rich Snippet Tool [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/wordpress-theme-plugin-reviews-in-extend/">WordPress Add Theme &#038; Plugin Reviews to Extend</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/alex-moss/">Alex Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Alex Moss";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3279:"<p>This morning we have noticed that WordPress.org users can now review both WordPress plugins and themes. This addition to WordPress Extend now provides more detail into users&#8217; thoughts, rather than the simple voting system that has been provided up until now.</p><h2>Rich Snippet Integration?</h2><p><img\nclass="size-full wp-image-2531 alignnone" title="wp-extend-img" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/wp-extend-img.jpg" alt="Facebook Comments Review" width="574" height="308" /><br\n/> <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/people/rhys-wynne/" target="_blank">Rhys</a> kindly <a\nhref="http://wordpress.org/support/view/plugin-reviews/facebook-comments-plugin">reviewed my Facebook Comments plugin</a>. From looking at Google&#8217;s <a\nhref="http://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/richsnippets?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwordpress.org%2Fsupport%2Fview%2Fplugin-reviews%2Ffacebook-comments-plugin&amp;html=">Rich Snippet Tool for this URL</a>, there does not seem to have any rich snippet integration yet. Instead, at the moment, it seems that the review capability is part of the support section for the plugin itself, where Rhys&#8217; comment actually <a\nhref="http://wordpress.org/support/topic/very-simple-plugin-for-getting-facebook-comments-on-your-blog?replies=1#post-">generates its own permalink</a> to which any other user can comment on. At the moment plugins are still integrating the star rating system into the SERPs:</p><p><img\nclass="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2524" title="facebook-comments-rich-snippet" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/facebook-comments-rich-snippet.png" alt="Facebook Comments Rich Snippet" width="517" height="112" /></p><h2>Complete Reviews Section Coming?</h2><p>As well as this, it seems that the breadcrumb within the permalink above, and also within a review for a theme, is part of a Review section located at the following URL - <strong>http://wordpress.org/support/forum/reviews</strong> &#8211; which at the moment 302 redirects back to the main support section of WordPress Extend.</p><h2>Sign of better quality Plugins?</h2><p>Although the Reviews section is not live as a complete section, I notice that reviews are beginning to populate, including <a\nhref="http://wordpress.org/support/view/theme-reviews/twentytwelve">Otto42&#8242;s review of TwentyTwelve</a> just a day ago. The review section could actually play a vital part in the success of a plugin or theme as users will be able to judge whether it adds value to their site and whether the plugin itself is trustworthy. Additionally, this section may also provide a good place for influential WordPress users to give their seal of approval for other plugins and themes &#8211; but then again this could just be a replacement to the current &#8220;voting&#8221; system which some people may not find useful.</p><p>What are your thoughts? Will this help you before you choose to download a plugin?</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/wordpress-theme-plugin-reviews-in-extend/">WordPress Add Theme &#038; Plugin Reviews to Extend</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/alex-moss/">Alex Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"http://3doordigital.com/wordpress-theme-plugin-reviews-in-extend/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"         ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:65:"Digital Roundup: Big Content, Link Spread, Disavow & Infographics";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:151:"http://3doordigital.com/link-spread-big-content-and-inforgraphics/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=link-spread-big-content-and-inforgraphics";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:75:"http://3doordigital.com/link-spread-big-content-and-inforgraphics/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 22 Oct 2012 10:05:17 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Digital Roundup";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2388";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:968:"<p>Welcome to another edition of the Digital Roundup. This roundup will cover some of the digital marketing articles that have been shared around the 3 Door Digital office over the last few weeks. Lets get started - &#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212; Why Big Content Is Worth the Risk Dr. Pete writes an in-depth article on how you should [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/link-spread-big-content-and-inforgraphics/">Digital Roundup: Big Content, Link Spread, Disavow &#038; Infographics</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/gideon-wellins/">Gideon Wellins</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Gideon Wellins";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10831:"<p><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-2470" title="digital-roundup-orange1" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/digital-roundup-orange1.jpg" alt="Digital Roundup" width="574" height="193" /><br\n/> Welcome to another edition of the Digital Roundup. This roundup will cover some of the digital marketing articles that have been shared around the 3 Door Digital office over the last few weeks. Lets get started -</p><p><span\nstyle="color: #c0c0c0;">&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</span></p><h2><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/08q7e">Why Big Content Is Worth the Risk</a></strong></h2><p>Dr. Pete writes an in-depth article on how you should spend your valuable time on creating “big content”, instead of exhausting the low-hanging fruit because it is easier to do.<br\n/> Big content takes effort, breaks molds but can also be small. With great effort comes great reward! One does not have to spend loads of cash on creating the content, but again it does take effort. The more you invest in big content the easier it becomes to grab the opportunities that are out there, the ones that are not easy to grab but take time, effort and commitment.</p><p>Dr Pete then provides some incredible examples:</p><p>SimplyBusiness  - a <a\nhref="http://www.simplybusiness.co.uk/microsites/wordpress-for-small-businesses/">WordPress Guide for Small Business</a>.</p><p><a\nhref="http://www.simplybusiness.co.uk/microsites/wordpress-for-small-businesses/" rel="attachment wp-att-2456"><img\nclass="alignnone  wp-image-2456" title="wordpress for small businesses" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/wordpress-for-small-businesses.png" alt="" width="543" height="494" /><br\n/> </a><span\nstyle="font-size: 12px;">Click image to open interactive version (via </span><a\nstyle="font-size: 12px;" href="http://www.simplybusiness.co.uk/">Simply Business</a><span\nstyle="font-size: 12px;">).</span></p><p>This infographic seems like it is a standard flowchart. However if you click on  “no” under each section a custom resource appears to answer the question. Some resource answers link out to help answer the question in more depth and some are links to videos specifically made for this project.</p><p>Another recent example by the folks at Seer Interactive, an interactive content piece called “<a\nhref="http://rcs.seerinteractive.com/money/">How Do They Make Money</a>”: Again, at first glance this looks like an ordinary infographic, but if you click on a company logo a content box pops up giving more information.</p><p><img\nsrc="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/fJ7VIkvGndur6DDzQTTr8KdU_neyMO50oQG88dXKY6M1Hn3IMQ948IeA66XO2BUYxnSaGLEs3tPzyOsCHaBw43uZuq_WKDZ1TPCHWG9-3DidxFFLfUWl" alt="" width="544px;" height="293px;" /></p><p>Both of these examples are useful, professional and really engage people.</p><p>Big content needs big concepts, but does not need to be long or large. This content takes a lot of time and effort, but done right the rewards can outway the investment tenfold. the example that Pete gives is his 1-page PDF that he created in February 2009, the 25-point usability checklist. Although he has spent almost no time on it in 2012 it has had over 55,000 page views and almost 50% of overall traffic to his site this year.</p><p>Big content drives traffic and links, but so does any successful content. Big content is set apart from successful content by a number of different factors.</p><ul><li>People come back to big content</li><li>Big content builds barriers that helps you stay ahead of the game whilst obtaining rankings, links, social mentions, builds brand, gets traffic and builds authority</li><li>Big content drives big ideas. <a\nhref="http://mozcast.com/">MozCast was born</a></li></ul><p>Don’t be afraid to try and it doesn’t have to cost a fortune. Keep motivated and keep at it.</p><p>Thanks to <a\nhref="http://twitter.com/@dr_pete">@dr_pete</a> for the use of his images.</p><p><span\nstyle="color: #c0c0c0;">&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</span></p><h2><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/eq1bt">How to Measure Your Link Spread<br\n/> </a></strong></h2><p>Chelsea Blacker explains how to show your link spread in a graph using tools that we use every day.</p><p>Link spread measures the number of internal links versus external links across a site. Chelsea explains that this exercise opens up a number of opportunities and illustrates what content is prioritised by the site owners versus what content has caught the attention of the wider web.</p><p><strong>5 Steps to Making Your Own Spread Graph</strong></p><p>The following three tools are needed:</p><p>1. Screaming Frog<br\n/> 2. MajesticSEO<br\n/> 3. Microsoft Excel</p><ul><li>Firstly you need to run a report in Screaming Frog and export the data.</li><li>Copy the columns titled “address” and “Inlinks” into a new sheet and name it “internallinks”.</li><li>The next step is to run a domain level report in MagesticSEO. Click the more detailed report on this domain URLs here link under the top pages/links section and export to CSV.</li><li>Copy the columns titled “URL” and “TotalBackLinks” into a new sheet called “externallinks”.</li><li>Merge the two sheets you created using the VLOOKUP command.<ul><li\nstyle="text-align: left;">In the internallinks sheet,  create a new row in column C and title it “external links” and create the following formula:</li></ul></li></ul><p\nstyle="text-align: center;">=VLOOKUP(<span\nstyle="color: #339966;">lookup_value</span>, <span\nstyle="color: #800000;">table_array</span>, <span\nstyle="color: #ff6600;">col_index_num</span>, [range_lookup])</p><p\nstyle="text-align: center;">=VLOOKUP(<span\nstyle="color: #339966;">A3</span>,<span\nstyle="color: #800000;">externallinks!$A$2:$B$72</span>,<span\nstyle="color: #ff6600;">2</span>,<span\nstyle="color: #0000ff;">FALSE</span>)</p><ul><li\nstyle="text-align: left;">Replace all “N/A” values with 0 using find and replace and then sort the inlinks from largest to smallest</li><li>Then build a simple link graph<ul><li>In the graph select the red (external links) line and goto insert &gt; chart  &gt; column &gt; clustered column.</li><li>Then create a secondary axis by clicking on the red bars and formating the selection which is found within layout.</li></ul></li></ul><p><strong><strong><br\n/> </strong></strong>For more details and screenshots go to <a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/eq1bt">Chelsea’s original post here</a>.</p><p><span\nstyle="color: #c0c0c0;">&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</span></p><h2><strong><a\nhref="http://dejanseo.com.au/google-link-disavow-complete-guide/">Google Link Disavow Tool: The Complete Guide<br\n/> </a></strong></h2><p>Dan Petrovic writes a thorough guide into the how, why and when to use this new tool.</p><p>The industry has gone through a major change in the past few days since the new &#8220;Google Link Disavow Tool&#8221; was released. This tool essentially allows webmasters to tell Google that they do not wish to be associated with chosen links and to please remove any relationship status that is linking them together. I recently took part in a Google+ hangout which Dan initiated where we discussed the disavow tool, link building and more. You can watch the video below:</p><p><object\nwidth="560" height="315" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param\nname="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param\nname="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param\nname="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/f1Ad9felc7I?version=3&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0" /><param\nname="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><embed\nwidth="560" height="315" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/f1Ad9felc7I?version=3&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0" allowFullScreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" /></object></p><p><span\nstyle="color: #c0c0c0;">&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</span></p><h2><strong><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/cvb1d">Free Template: How to Easily Create Infographics in PowerPoint</a></strong></h2><p>This one is short and sweet &#8211; Hubspot released a great “how to” for creating infographics with powerpoint. You can <a\nhref="http://www.hubspot.com/free-template-easily-create-infographics-in-powerpoint/" target="_blank">download it</a> from their site. The templates provide a step-by-step tutorial for creating infographics. You can use these templates to kickstart and give you motivation for content curation ideas. Check it out.</p><p><span\nstyle="color: #c0c0c0;">&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</span></p><p>Other articles or tips that you may find interesting are:</p><ul><li><a\nhref="http://searchengineland.com/google-penguin-update-3-135527" target="_blank">Google Penguin Update 3 Released</a></li><li><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/iwfep">It’s “Top Heavy 2″ As Google Rolls Out Update To Its Page Layout Algorithm</a></li><li><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/d7zo4">Back To The Future: Google Announces A Meta Keywords Tag Just For News Articles</a></li><li><a\nhref="http://3doo.rs/htjnd">12 Content Research Tools You Should Be Using</a></li></ul><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/link-spread-big-content-and-inforgraphics/">Digital Roundup: Big Content, Link Spread, Disavow &#038; Infographics</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/gideon-wellins/">Gideon Wellins</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:71:"http://3doordigital.com/link-spread-big-content-and-inforgraphics/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"         ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:87:"Advanced WordPress SEO: Add Custom Values to Permalinks Through Custom Fields and Posts";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:171:"http://3doordigital.com/custom-fields-and-posts-in-wordpress-permalink-urls/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=custom-fields-and-posts-in-wordpress-permalink-urls";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:85:"http://3doordigital.com/custom-fields-and-posts-in-wordpress-permalink-urls/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 17 Oct 2012 12:36:31 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2351";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:733:"<p>Recently here at 3 Door Digital we had a project that required pretty advanced custom URL structures in WordPress. By default, WordPress is pretty good with permalinks, allowing you to specify a whole range of variables to use. For most websites that use WordPress as their Content Management System, you will probably use one of the [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/custom-fields-and-posts-in-wordpress-permalink-urls/">Advanced WordPress SEO: Add Custom Values to Permalinks Through Custom Fields and Posts</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/rhys-wynne/">Rhys Wynne</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Rhys Wynne";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10915:"<p\nstyle="text-align: center;"><img\nclass="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2431" title="wordpress-code-snippets" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/wordpress-code-snippets1.png" alt="Wordpress Code Header Snippet" width="574" height="176" /></p><p>Recently here at 3 Door Digital we had a project that required pretty advanced custom URL structures in WordPress. By default, WordPress is pretty good with permalinks, allowing you to <a\nhref="http://codex.wordpress.org/Using_Permalinks" target="_blank">specify a whole range of variables</a> to use. For most websites that use WordPress as their Content Management System, you will probably use one of the default permalink structures. However suppose you are working on a website &#8211; say for example a law firm &#8211; and you want to list all solicitors associated with the firm, as well as their specialty. Suppose you want each solicitor to have the following URL structure:-</p><pre>/solicitors/specialty/solicitors-name/</pre><p>How could you do this? You could create individual pages for each solicitor, and nest each page within each speciality. However this could create a lot of redundant pages, and could take a fair amount of time. Alternatively you could use custom posts and custom fields, as well as a little bit of  URL rewriting using WordPress&#8217;s internal functions. You can recreate the example URL structure fairly easily this way, here&#8217;s how:</p><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>1. Create A Custom Post Type</h2><p>To begin with, we need to create a custom post type called &#8220;Solicitors&#8221;. This will add an extra menu entitled &#8220;Solicitors&#8221; to the sidebar in the administration section of WordPress. These posts, separate from your standard posts and pages, will not appear in any blog, but can have added custom fields added to it &#8211; in this case &#8220;Speciality&#8221;.</p><p>In your favourite code editor (I recommend <a\nhref="http://notepad-plus-plus.org/" target="_blank">NotePad++</a> for free, or <a\nhref="http://www.mpsoftware.dk/phpdesigner.php" target="_blank">PHPDesigner8</a> for a paid editor, though Adobe Dreamweaver if you have it is fine), open your WordPress theme&#8217;s functions.php, and copy and paste the following lines:-</p><pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">\nfunction tdd_create_custom_post_type() {\nregister_post_type( ''solicitors'',\narray(\n''labels'' =&gt; array(\n''name'' =&gt; __( ''Solicitors'' ),\n''singular_name'' =&gt; __( ''Solicitor'' )\n),\n''public'' =&gt; true,\n''has_archive'' =&gt; true,\n''rewrite'' =&gt; FALSE,\n)\n);\n}\n\nadd_action( ''init'', ''tdd_create_custom_post_type'' );\n</pre><p>This will create a custom post type using the <a\nhref="http://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/register_post_type" target="_blank">register_post_type function</a> that will display whenever an admin page is displayed. So you&#8217;re not blindly copy and pasting, here is each line in the code explained:-</p><ul><li><strong>register_post_type(&#8216;solicitors</strong>, &#8230; <strong>- </strong>this registers a post type called solicitors with an array of options specified, the options specified are:-<ul><li><strong>&#8216;labels&#8217; </strong>- the name (in English) of your post type &#8211; this is what is displayed on screen. You can also specify a singular name using the variable singular_name</li><li><strong>&#8216;public&#8217; </strong>- This should be true, as you want people to see your post, right? <img\nsrc=''http://3doordigital.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif'' alt='':)'' class=''wp-smiley'' /></li><li><strong>&#8216;has_archive&#8217;</strong> &#8211; This specifies if that if all posts in question have an archive page or not. I usually set this to false.</li><li><strong>&#8216;rewrite&#8217;</strong> &#8211; This specifies if URL&#8217;s for this post type should be rewritten, and if so how. By default, solicitors posts would have the URL /solicitors/solicitors-name/. As we are specifying the URL rewrite rules, we<em> need</em> it to be false.</li></ul></li><li><strong>add_action( &#8216;init&#8217;, &#8216;create_custom_post_type&#8217; ); </strong>- As soon as possible when the blog loads, run the &#8220;create_custom_post_type&#8221; function.</li></ul><div><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2></div><h2>2. Add a Custom Field to a Custom Post Type</h2><p>We then need to create a custom field associated with this post type. The easiest way to do this is by adding a box that only appears on the page associated with the custom post type. To do this, copy and paste this into your theme&#8217;s functions.php file:-</p><pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">\n\nfunction tdd_custom_metabox() {\nglobal $post;\n\n//Get All the Data for the Post In Question\n$solicitorspeciality = get_post_meta( $post-&gt;ID, ''posts_solicitorspeciality'', true );\n\n// output invlid url message and add the http:// to the input field (will be added later)\nif( $errors ) { echo $errors; } ?&gt;\n\n&lt;!-- Build The Box in Question --&gt;\n\n&lt;label for=&quot;solicitorspeciality&quot;&gt;The speciality area of this Solicitor\n\n&lt;input id=&quot;solicitorspeciality&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;solicitorspeciality&quot; value=&quot;&lt;?php if( $solicitorspeciality ) { echo $solicitorspeciality; } ?&gt;&quot; size=&quot;37&quot; /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n\n&lt;!--?php } /** * Process the custom metabox fields */ function tdd_save_custom_metabox( $post_id ) { global $post; if( $_POST ) { update_post_meta( $post---&gt;ID, ''posts_solicitorspeciality'', $_POST[''solicitorspeciality''] );\n}\n}\n\n/**\n* Add meta box\n*/\nfunction tdd_add_custom_metabox() {\nadd_meta_box( ''custom-metabox'', __( ''Specialty of the Solicitor'' ), ''tdd_custom_metabox'', ''solicitors'', ''normal'', ''high'' );\n}\n\nadd_action( ''admin_init'', ''tdd_add_custom_metabox'' );\nadd_action( ''save_post'', ''tdd_save_custom_metabox'' );\n\n</pre><p>Here is what each line of the code does:-</p><ul><li><strong>Lines 2-17</strong> builds a meta box which adds a &#8220;speciality&#8221; field. If the current post has a &#8220;speciality&#8221; defined already (i.e. it&#8217;s not empty), this is prepopulated when the post loads.</li><li><strong>Lines 22-28</strong> saves to the database the value of the speciality field for that post whenever the post is saved.</li><li><strong>Lines 33-35</strong> adds the &#8220;speciality&#8221; field to a custom meta box on any post that is a &#8220;solicitor&#8221; (as we only want the box appearing on a &#8220;solicitor&#8221; post type, not every post or page). The box title is &#8220;Speciality of the Solicitor&#8221; and the contents of the meta box is the output of the &#8220;tdd_custom_metabox&#8221; function.</li><li><strong>Line 37</strong> states that if we are currently on an administration page, we run the tdd_add_custom_metabox function to see if we can add the meta box created in lines 2-17.</li><li><strong>Line 38</strong> makes sure that lines 22-28 are run whenever a post is saved.</li></ul><div><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2></div><h2>3. Build the Post URL Using The Custom Field</h2><p>You now need to rewrite the URL adding in the custom field to the URL. To do this we use two WordPress functions &#8211; <a\nhref="http://codex.wordpress.org/Rewrite_API/add_rewrite_tag" target="_blank">add_rewrite_tag </a>and <a\nhref="http://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_permastruct" target="_blank">add_permastruct</a>.</p><p>These two functions basically change the URL structure so that we can add more data into the URL, which will then be changed back to a standard permalink. This is all done on the fly, before WordPress even loads the page, so users aren&#8217;t aware of it happening.</p><p>To begin with, we will create the function that will change the permalink structure. Copy and paste the following into your functions.php file:-</p><pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">\n\nadd_action(''init'', ''tdd_add_rewrite_rules'');\n\nfunction tdd_add_rewrite_rules()\n\n{\n\n// Register custom rewrite rules\n\nglobal $wp_rewrite;\n$wp_rewrite-&gt;add_rewrite_tag(''%solicitors%'', ''([^/]+)'', ''solicitors='');\n$wp_rewrite-&gt;add_rewrite_tag(''%posts_solicitorspeciality%'', ''([^/]+)'', ''posts_solicitorspeciality='');\n\n$wp_rewrite-&gt;add_permastruct(''solicitors'', ''/%posts_solicitorspeciality%/%solicitors%'', false);\n\n}\n\n</pre><p>If you try creating a custom post now, you won&#8217;t be able to access any post. The reason being that the URL of the blog post will contain the phrase %posts_solicitorspeciality%, which is invalid.</p><p>We now need to replace all instances of %posts_solicitorspeciality% with the value of the custom field, when the post is created. To do this, paste the following into your functions.php file.</p><pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">\n\nadd_filter(''post_type_link'', ''tdd_permalinks'', 10, 3);\n\nfunction tdd_permalinks($permalink, $post, $leavename)\n\n{\n\n$no_data = ''no-speciality'';\n\n$post_id = $post-&gt;ID;\n\nif($post-&gt;post_type != ''solicitors'' || empty($permalink) || in_array($post-&gt;post_status, array(''draft'', ''pending'', ''auto-draft'')))\n\nreturn $permalink;\n\n$var1 = get_post_meta($post_id, ''posts_solicitorspeciality'', true);\n\n$var1 = sanitize_title($var1);\n\nif(!$var1) { $var1 = $no_data; }\n\n$permalink = str_replace(''%posts_solicitorspeciality%'', $var1, $permalink);\n\nreturn $permalink;\n\n}</pre><p>This will replace all instances of %posts_solicitorspeciality% with the value of the speciality field. If nothing is there, then the value &#8220;no-speciality&#8221; will be used in the URL. This is to avoid the URL structure of /solicitors//solicitor-name.</p><p>That&#8217;s pretty much it! You can do some advanced jiggery pokery to add on more variables to the URL, creating subfolders and subfolders. I talk about this in the download below. You can download a copy of the above code to copy or paste (or include) into functions.php.</p><p>To download the code, which is far more annotated, click the link below:-</p><p><a\nclass="btn btn-success conbtn" href="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/adding-custom-fields-to-permalinks.zip">Click Here To Download</a></p><p>Any queries, please let us know in the comments!</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/custom-fields-and-posts-in-wordpress-permalink-urls/">Advanced WordPress SEO: Add Custom Values to Permalinks Through Custom Fields and Posts</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/rhys-wynne/">Rhys Wynne</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"http://3doordigital.com/custom-fields-and-posts-in-wordpress-permalink-urls/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"         ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"Welcome Rhys Wynne! Our new Digital Marketing Consultant";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:105:"http://3doordigital.com/welcome-rhys-wynne/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=welcome-rhys-wynne";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:52:"http://3doordigital.com/welcome-rhys-wynne/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 02 Oct 2012 09:20:51 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Company News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2311";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:660:"<p>Things are moving fast here at 3 Door Digital, following our July 2012 launch we have won some exciting new marketing clients as well as some great WordPress development projects &#8211; we recently completed v.1 of the WordPress plugin for MyBlogGuest and more updates for that are on the way! Following this, we are delighted [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/welcome-rhys-wynne/">Welcome Rhys Wynne! Our new Digital Marketing Consultant</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/marc-levy/">Marc Levy</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Marc Levy";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2391:"<p>Things are moving fast here at 3 Door Digital, following our <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/if-google-hangout-were-a-person/">July 2012 launch</a> we have won some exciting new marketing clients as well as some great WordPress development projects &#8211; we recently completed v.1 of the <a\nhref="http://myblogguest.com/blog/guest-blogging-wordpress-plugin/" target="_blank">WordPress plugin for MyBlogGuest</a> and more updates for that are on the way!</p><p>Following this, we are delighted to announce that <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/people/rhys-wynne/">Rhys Wynne</a> will joining our UK team. We&#8217;re sure Rhys will be an excellent addition to our growing team and we&#8217;re very excited to have him on board. Rhys wanted to introduce himself, so over to him..</p><blockquote><p><img\nclass="size-full wp-image-2331 alignright" title="rhys-in-action" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/rhys-in-action.png" alt="Rhys Wynne" width="400" height="191" />Hi, I’m Rhys Wynne, and I’m excited to be starting my new role as a Digital Marketing Consultant here at 3 Door Digital.</p><p>A little about me – I am a SEO consultant with over 5 years experience in Commercial SEO, spread between my home in North Wales, as well as for a larger agency in Manchester. SEO and the internet isn’t a day job for me, as in my spare time <a\nhref="http://youresupposedtobeathome.com" target="_blank">I blog about sports</a>, <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/rhyswynne">tweet a fair bit</a> and develop WordPress plugins, some of which <a\nhref="http://wpemailcapture.com/">I sell online</a>.</p><p>My new position will allow me to broaden my Digital Marketing skill set as well as offer me the opportunity to work across a number of WordPress development projects, both of which I am extremely excited about. I am also keen to develop my commercial development skills and I feel that the opportunity at 3 Door Digital is going to provide me with exactly this.</p><p>I look forward to working with the staff and clients of 3 Door Digital!</p></blockquote><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/welcome-rhys-wynne/">Welcome Rhys Wynne! Our new Digital Marketing Consultant</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/marc-levy/">Marc Levy</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"http://3doordigital.com/welcome-rhys-wynne/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"         ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"#BrightonSEO in Bullet Points";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:125:"http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=brightonseo-in-bullet-points";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 18 Sep 2012 09:12:14 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Conferences";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://3doordigital.com/?p=2293";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:608:"<p>I attended our first Brighton SEO and can say that Kelvin really does organise a great event. As a one day event with over 1,500 attendees, it was great to see such a range of topics covered from various key people in online and advertising. Here are some selective notes I wanted to share in [...]</p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/">#BrightonSEO in Bullet Points</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/alex-moss/">Alex Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Alex Moss";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12471:"<p><img\nclass="alignnone size-full wp-image-2305" title="brighton-seo-main" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/brighton-seo-main.gif" alt="BrightonSEO" width="574" height="193" /><br\n/> I attended our first Brighton SEO and can say that Kelvin really does organise a great event. As a one day event with over 1,500 attendees, it was great to see such a range of topics covered from various key people in online and advertising.</p><p>Here are some selective notes I wanted to share in bulletpoint form:</p><h2>Keynote &#8211; Dave Trott on &#8220;Predatory Thinking&#8221;</h2><blockquote\nclass="twitter-tweet" width="500"><p>Smart thinking: <a\nhref="http://t.co/gYNZVLk4" title="http://www.predatorythinking.com/a-gap-in-the-market/">predatorythinking.com/a-gap-in-the-m…</a></p><p>&mdash; dave trott (@davetrott) <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/davetrott/status/246917936013516800" data-datetime="2012-09-15T10:26:38+00:00">September 15, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/2012-09-14-10-04-01/" rel="attachment wp-att-2297"><img\nclass="alignright size-medium wp-image-2297" title="2012-09-14 10.04.01" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/2012-09-14-10.04.01-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p><ul><li>Whatever you do, stand out</li><li>Predatory thinking are principles on how to kill the competition</li><li>Form follows function<ul><li>First is form. Start with reason and justify it</li><li>Function is the application of the form</li></ul></li><li>Separate yourself from your own thinking</li><li>Viral is all about the punter. &#8220;Viral&#8221; was before youtube, internet and radio. Word of mouth is virality.</li><li>Conversation has 3 elements<ol><li>Impact</li><li>Communication</li><li>Persuasion</li></ol></li><li>Complication is weakness, simplicity is strength</li><li>Einstein quoted something that is still relevant today: &#8220;if you cant explain to 11yr old you dont understand it&#8221;</li><li>You must adopt a language for your clients and another language for punters.</li><li>More time needed on the &#8220;impact&#8221; part of a great conversation. 90% fails by spending too much on &#8220;persuasion&#8221;. If you don&#8217;t get seen then nothing else will work.</li><li>Selective persuasion is a great tool. For example, if you are thinking of buying a new car, you will suddenly see them everywhere on the road.</li><li>Direct Line has an advertising budget of £83m pa. How can you stand out against that if you only have £5m?<ul><li>Opinion formers want to stand out. They&#8217;re usually the centre of a conversation.</li><li>Opinion followers are most people. Like to listen to the opinion former.</li></ul></li><li>The trick is to create something an opinion former will acknowledge and later speak about. So, how do you get an opinion former&#8217;s attention? You have got to be different. It&#8217;s a risk but if you stand out you;ll win.</li><li>Predatory thinking is applied creativity<ul><li>Adverts about drink driving ads are a good example. Targeting the drunk person didn&#8217;t work so instead ads were targeted at the sober person with the message &#8220;if you&#8217;re a real friend you won&#8217;t let your friend drive drunk&#8221;. This was much more effective.</li></ul></li><li>Go upstream to do what you need</li></ul><div>As you can see there&#8217;s a lot Dave makes you think about. He has also written a <a\nhref="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Creative-Mischief-1-Dave-Trott/dp/095643570X/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1347887584&amp;sr=1-1" rel="external">book on the subject</a>.</div><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>Steph Troeth on User Experience</h2><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/2012-09-14-12-22-13/" rel="attachment wp-att-2299"><img\nclass="alignright size-medium wp-image-2299" title="2012-09-14 12.22.13" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/2012-09-14-12.22.13-300x224.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="224" /></a></p><ul><li>What makes a great unique product?</li><li>Brand can describe product &#8211; such as exotic, reliable, fun etc</li><li>Add geek factor to your products</li><li>Think of different uses for your products</li><li>How do we want people to experience us? Create a two column table &#8211; &#8220;emotion&#8221; and &#8220;rational&#8221;</li><li>Stephanie Hay once spoke about designing for content. Create a message hierarchy<ul><li>Message for users</li><li>Associated business purpose</li><li>Underlying Business outcome</li></ul></li></ul><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>Martin Belam: &#8220;How to Make Friends and Influence Robots&#8221;</h2><blockquote\nclass="twitter-tweet" width="500"><p>“How to make friends. And influence robots” &#8211; the blog post of the talk I gave today at <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/search/%23BrightonSEO">#BrightonSEO</a> <a\nhref="http://t.co/TyPnQjNU" title="http://www.currybet.net/cbet_blog/2012/09/how-to-make-friends-and-influence-robots.php">currybet.net/cbet_blog/2012…</a></p><p>&mdash; Martin Belam (@currybet) <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/currybet/status/246586163278794755" data-datetime="2012-09-14T12:28:17+00:00">September 14, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><div><ul><li>Headlines &#8211; ensure its in context and how it&#8217;ll look when shared</li><li>Navigation is really important for humans and spiderability</li><li>Always study visitor flow</li><li>Performance is key</li><li>Think about unintended consequences &#8211; conversion moreso</li></ul><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>Will Critchlow on APIs (filling in for Tom Anthony)</h2><blockquote\nclass="twitter-tweet" width="500"><p>Is the web going to give way to other plaforms? &#8220;The role of APIs in the Future of Search&#8221;: <a\nhref="http://t.co/OMq6ZNBp" title="http://www.seomoz.org/blog/apis-future-of-search">seomoz.org/blog/apis-futu…</a></p><p>&mdash; Tom Anthony (@TomAnthonySEO) <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/TomAnthonySEO/status/247650877282865152" data-datetime="2012-09-17T10:59:04+00:00">September 17, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/2012-09-14-12-53-14/" rel="attachment wp-att-2300"><img\nclass="alignright size-medium wp-image-2300" title="2012-09-14 12.53.14" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/2012-09-14-12.53.14-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p><div><ul><li>Over ten years weve gone from general searches to specific searches</li><li>Five years will see decline of web pages and more API use</li><li>Google glasses is example of API use</li><li>Computers retrieving information from compauters is becoming a great way for information retrieval. Being able to use an API can give more targeted results to the user</li></ul><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>Richard Baxter on &#8220;What Makes a Good SEO&#8221;</h2><blockquote\nclass="twitter-tweet" width="500"><p>How to Be a Better SEO &#8211; <a\nhref="https://t.co/8Uq1zcWv" title="https://seogadget.co.uk/better-seo/">seogadget.co.uk/better-seo/</a> earlier I addressed <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/search/%23brightonseo">#brightonseo</a> &#8211; this is what I said&#8230;</p><p>&mdash; Richard Baxter (@richardbaxter) <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/richardbaxter/status/246657208421609473" data-datetime="2012-09-14T17:10:35+00:00">September 14, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><div><ul><li>Set goals</li><li>Be entrepenerial</li><li>Be able to sell yourself</li><li>Rehearse everything</li><li>Learn a specialism</li><li>Build your own website</li><li>Learn to sell anything</li><li>Convey you care what you do</li><li>Always follow up</li><li>Know your figures</li><li>Communicate successes</li><li>Leadership comes from certainty which comes from confidence</li></ul><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>Aleyda Solis on Mobile SEO</h2><blockquote\nclass="twitter-tweet" width="500"><p>Thank you <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/search/%23brightonSEO">#brightonSEO</a>! You can take a closer look at my presentation about <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/search/%23mobileSEO">#mobileSEO</a> here: <a\nhref="http://t.co/R69oFFGe" title="http://bit.ly/domobileseo">bit.ly/domobileseo</a></p><p>&mdash; Aleyda Solís (@aleyda) <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/aleyda/status/246642222865469440" data-datetime="2012-09-14T16:11:02+00:00">September 14, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><div><ol><li>What is the mobile users behaviour? Use <a\nhref="http://www.google.com/analytics/">Google Analytics</a></li><li>What is site behaviour in mobile SERPs? <a\nhref="https://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/home?hl=en">Google Webmaster Tools</a> has info on this</li><li>Audience behaviour in mobile search? Use <a\nhref="http://adwords.google.co.uk/o/Targeting/Explorer?__u=1000000000&amp;__c=1000000000&amp;ideaRequestType=KEYWORD_IDEAS">Google&#8217;s Keyword tool</a></li><li>How is site viewed? Fetch as mobile within Webmaster Tools (also, I use <a\nhref="http://screenqueri.es/">Screenqueri.es</a>)</li><li>What is content and product offer? Use local attributes if possible</li><li>What is tech capacity? Mobile specific site, responsive CSS or dynamic serving</li><li>Decide on type of mobile site you need</li></ol><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><h2>Yousef Yeksland on Reverse Engineering Your Competitors</h2><blockquote\nclass="twitter-tweet" width="500"><p>I wrote a detailed post on Reverse Engineering Your Competitors Social/Content Strategy <a\nhref="http://t.co/IQXW1O2Q" title="http://www.rocketmill.co.uk/reverse-engineering-your-competitors-socialcontent-strategy">rocketmill.co.uk/reverse-engine…</a> <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/search/%23brightonseo">#brightonseo</a></p><p>&mdash; Yousaf (@ysekand) <a\nhref="https://twitter.com/ysekand/status/246908635580600320" data-datetime="2012-09-15T09:49:40+00:00">September 15, 2012</a></p></blockquote><p><script src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></p><div><ul><li>Content isn&#8217;t king, it&#8217;s Kingmaker</li><li>Producing great content is not easy and not cheap</li><li>See what worked for a competitor, then leaverage it</li><li>Use <a\nhref="http://socialcrawlytics.com/">Social Crawlytics</a> to analyse what pages within a domain are shared most.</li><li>Use <a\nhref="http://backtweets.com/">Backtweets</a> for who shared what on social networks.</li><li>Also use <a\nhref="http://topsy.com/">Topsy</a> and <a\nhref="http://datasift.com/">Datasift</a></li></ul><h2><img\ntitle="blue-line-break" src="http://www.3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/blue-line-break.png" alt="" width="566" height="28" /></h2><p><strong>It was also nice to see Justin Beiber drop in for a quick appearance. Here he is having a drink with us all</strong></p><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/2012-09-14-23-47-38/" rel="attachment wp-att-2301"><img\nclass="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-2301" title="2012-09-14 23.47.38" src="http://3doordigital.com/wp-content/uploads/2012-09-14-23.47.38-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p></div></div></div></div></div><p><a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com/brightonseo-in-bullet-points/">#BrightonSEO in Bullet Points</a> was written by <a\nrel="author" href="http://3doordigital.com/people/alex-moss/">Alex Moss</a> of <a\nhref="http://3doordigital.com">3 Door Digital</a>, a digital marketing agency in the UK and Israel</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"http://3doordigita