";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:153:"<p>More and more themes in WordPress make use of the &#8220;featured image&#8221; capabilities of WordPress.  The ability to embed images in a the...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Total Bounty";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5001:"<p>More and more themes in WordPress make use of the &#8220;featured image&#8221; capabilities of WordPress.  The ability to embed images in a theme have been available for a long time, but often you use and re-use images for similar categories or themes, or just have an image to associate with the post or page.</p>\n<p>To be able to actually display the featured image with your post, your WP theme has to be coded properly (and both 2010 and 2011 default themes are). Most modern themes are setup this way as well.  When you create new pages and posts on the right sidebar you&#8217;ll see this:</p>\n<p><img src="http://www.totalbounty.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/wordpress-featured-image.png" alt="wordpress featured image" title="wordpress-featured-image" width="284" height="71" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1038" /></p>\n<p>Then when you click the link you get the media uploader, and just click the link for featured image to attached to your post or page:</p>\n<p><img src="http://www.totalbounty.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/wordpress-featured-image2.png" alt="how to set a featured image" title="how to set a featured image" width="389" height="222" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1039" /></p>\n<p>If your theme isn&#8217;t already setup for featured posts, just add this code to the page templates you want to use that image on (index.php, archive.php, tag.php, category.php, single.php, etc.).  This code is automated so it will take the first image from your post, and make it the featured image (a thumbnail version).  So you could have the full size version on your post (single.php) and then this code would automatically take that first image and use the thumbnail version on the homepage (home.php or index.php), or archives (archive.php, tag,php, category.php).</p>\n<p>&lt;?php<br />\nfunction autoset_featured() {<br />\nglobal $post;<br />\n$already_has_thumb = has_post_thumbnail($post-&gt;ID);<br />\nif (!$already_has_thumb)  {<br />\n$attached_image = get_children( &#8220;post_parent=$post-&gt;ID&amp;post_type=attachment&amp;post_mime_type=image&amp;numberposts=1&#8243; );<br />\nif ($attached_image) {<br />\nforeach ($attached_image as $attachment_id =&gt; $attachment) {<br />\nset_post_thumbnail($post-&gt;ID, $attachment_id);<br />\n}<br />\n}<br />\n}<br />\n}<br />\nadd_action(&#8216;the_post&#8217;, &#8216;autoset_featured&#8217;);<br />\nadd_action(&#8216;save_post&#8217;, &#8216;autoset_featured&#8217;);<br />\nadd_action(&#8216;draft_to_publish&#8217;, &#8216;autoset_featured&#8217;);<br />\nadd_action(&#8216;new_to_publish&#8217;, &#8216;autoset_featured&#8217;);<br />\nadd_action(&#8216;pending_to_publish&#8217;, &#8216;autoset_featured&#8217;);<br />\nadd_action(&#8216;future_to_publish&#8217;, &#8216;autoset_featured&#8217;);<br />\n?&gt;</p>\n<p>In the code you can change &#8220;thumbnail&#8221; to the size medium, large, or full (all supported by the media uploader) to use that version as the featured image instead.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wpforce.com/automatically-set-the-featured-image-in-wordpress/">Hat tip to WP Force</a>.</p>\n<div class="aizattos_related_posts"><span class="aizattos_related_posts_header" >Related Posts</span><ul><li><span class="aizattos_related_posts_title"><a href="http://www.totalbounty.com/324/wordpress-gravity-forms-plugin-review