the head of your theme&#8217;s HTML code is a statement that displays the version of WordPre...</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Total Bounty";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3859:"<p>If you are using WordPress to power your website, in the head of your theme&#8217;s HTML code is a statement that displays the version of WordPress you&#8217;re using. This is called the &#8220;meta generator&#8221; tag that WordPress places there by default. This is considered by most experts to be a security risk (even though it&#8217;s good advertising for WordPress).</p>\n<p>Day and night automated bots and hacking scripts try to attack your website, don&#8217;t give them any edge to try and break into your website. The count on the fact that the majority of WordPress websites have embedded in the HTML code the fact that they are running on WordPress (and what version it is).</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s say the meta generator tag in the HTML code of your website says this:</p>\n<p>Now let&#8217;s say version 3.3.2 came out yesterday, and a huge security exploit was fixed (and you&#8217;re in the Bahamas on vaction for 2 weeks).</p>\n<p>As soon as that security exploit is announced, hackers are going to start scanning the web looking for sites with a meta generator tag of WordPress 3.3.1 (or prior) &#8211; knowing that they can use that exploit to break into your website (because you haven&#8217;t updated yet).</p>\n<p>There are a couple things you could do &#8211; you could <a href="www.totalbounty.com/169/how-to-harden-wordpress-security-easily/">learn how to harden security with a plugin</a>. The plugin in that blog tutorial is fairly comprehensive, there&#8217;s actually a more lightweight one called <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/secure-wordpress/">Secure WordPress</a> as well.</p>\n<p>The other option (if you know how to edit your own theme code) is to add a simple PHP code snipped to your functions.php or header.php file in of your WP theme like this:</p>\n<p>&lt;?php remove_action(&#8216;wp_head&#8217;, &#8216;wp_generator&#8217;); ?&gt;</p>\n<p>There you go &#8211; with that one simple line of code your website is now a bit more secure!</p>\n<div class="aizattos_related_posts"><span class="aizattos_related_posts_header" >Related Posts</span><ul><li><span class="aizattos_related_posts_title"><a href="http://www.totalbounty.com/158/how-to-setup-wordpress-seo-by-yoast-video/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: How to Setup WordPress SEO by Yoast Video" >How to Setup WordPress SEO by Yoast Video</a></span><div class="aizattos_related_posts_excerpt">For years the default SEO plugin for WordPress was All in One SEO Pack.  It was what everybody used ...</div></li><li><span class="aizattos_related_posts_title"><a href="http://www.totalbounty.com/391/top-wordpress-plugins-for-beginners/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: Top WordPress Plugins for Beginners" >Top WordPress Plugins for Beginners</a></span><div class="aizattos_related_posts_excerpt">If you are new to WordPress you’ve probably heard about plugins and notice how people can go crazy...</div></li><li><span class="aizattos_related_posts_title"><a href="http://www.totalbounty.com/forums/reply/reply-to-wordpress-text-message-11/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: Reply To: WordPress Text Message" >Reply To: WordPress Text Message</a></span><div class="aizattos_related_posts_excerpt">@jonnyj771 - must be something with godaddy - I don''t know.  Are all the WP installs you''ve tried it...</div></li><li><span class="aizattos_related_posts_title"><a href="http://www.totalbounty.com/864/wordpress-text-message-plugin-2-08-released/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent L